      "content": "Hey! I’m glad you’re asking because a broken hollandaise is a classic problem, and I’ve got a quick fix that should bring your sauce back to life. The “oil‑and‑curdle” look usually means the emulsion broke because the butter didn’t melt evenly or the egg yolk wasn’t whisked fast enough. Think of it like a tiny goblin‑cooked sauce that fell apart—just as a goblin might slip on a slick floor, your sauce slipped out of its perfect emulsion.\n\n**Why it happens**  \n1. **Heat & Timing** – The butter must melt slowly while you whisk the egg yolk. If the heat is too high or you whisk too slowly, the fat separates and looks oily.  \n2. **Whisking Speed** – A quick, vigorous whisk keeps the fat droplets suspended. A slow whisk lets them clump and create that curdled look.  \n3. **Acid Balance** – A little lemon juice or vinegar can help stabilize the emulsion, but too much acid can also cause separation if you’re not careful.\n\n**How to fix it**  \n1. **Re‑heat the sauce** – Put the broken sauce back on",
